\begin_layout Section*
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That we operate in an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Information-Age Economy
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

has been a cliché for a generation (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Shapiro1998"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Peter Drucker anticipated as early as the late 1950s the emergence of 
\shape italic
knowledge work
\shape default
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Wartzman2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 He subsequently foresaw that, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

knowledge 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle$
\end_inset

becomes
\begin_inset Formula $\rangle$
\end_inset

 a more-crucial economic resource than land, labor, or financial assets,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Drucker1992"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) leading to what he called a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

post-capitalist society
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Porter and Millar (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Porter1985"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) observed 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the information revolution sweeping through our economy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the mid-1980s.
 They provided heuristic descriptions of informational impacts in terms
 of existing value-chain frameworks for the analysis of strategy.
 Although this early work did not anticipate early-21
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
st
\end_layout

\end_inset

-century emergent operating models, likely strategic impacts were described.
 These included improved operational efficiencies, more-tailored responsiveness
 to market pulls, and adaptively shifting competitive scope.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider here the broader strategic implications of information, beyond
 just operational efficiency.
 
\shape italic
If
\shape default
 knowledge is indeed a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

more-crucial resource than land, labor, or financial assets
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\shape italic
then
\shape default
 its significance certainly must be in some regards strategic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Information is, in fact, the stuff that feeds decision-making — whether
 it be strategic or mundanely operational (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kochebnderfer2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Certainly, decision-making can be a strategic activity (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Leiblein2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Recently, high degrees of concentration of information under the control
 of a small number of large technology firms have led to commensurate concentrat
ions of marketplace power (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Iansiti2017,Bond2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 The development of methods to attribute economic value to information are
 correspondingly emerging topics of interest for both research and regulation
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Foroohar2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We undertake here the ambitious task of formulating a generalized framework
 for characterizing competitive differentiation based on information.
 The discipline of Information Economics provides our foundation (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Laffont1989,Birchler1999,Brunnermeier2001"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 This field is exactly focused on informational-value attribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Information Economics finds its most-common applications in financial markets.
 It provides theories and operating concepts for markets and their equilibria.
 Its principles also influence quantitative — or algorithmic — trading (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Narang2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This study proceeds as follows.
 We first introduce the relevant principles from Information Economics.
 We make the case for their employment as bases for understanding information-ba
sed competitive differentiation.
 We treat these basic principles as axioms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From these axioms, three distinct modes of information-based differentiation
 emerge.
 We further explore each mode in turn.
 We first revisit how our information-economic axioms appear for a given
 mode of differentiation mode.
 We then examine exemplary operating models conforming to that mode.
 We finally consider the defensibility of advantages based on each mode.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We conclude with an outline in broad strokes of a framework for thinking
 about 
\shape italic
Return on Information
\shape default
.
 The potential to deliberately frame an organization's 
\shape italic
Strategic Information Agenda
\shape default
 results.
 This is consistent with the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\shape italic
strategizing before strategic decision-making
\shape default

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 methodology by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Nickerson2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It occurs in the end that a strategic information agenda seeks to align
 technology and other organizational competencies in order to realize a
 defensible, differentiated position in the marketplace.
 This is consistent with observations from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kane2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 that, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Strategy, not technology, drives digital transformation.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Moreover, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "LaValle2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 recommend, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Start with the questions, not the data.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
The Information Economics of Competitive Differentiation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Information Economics seeks to systematically attribute economic value to
 information.
 The field resides at the nexus of three other disciplines.
 We synopsize them here and motivate their generalization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, Information Theory characterizes uncertainty and information.
 It spans two branches.
 Its probability-and-statistics view came from the telecommunications industry
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Shannon1948,Gallagher1968"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Borrowing from the field of statistical thermodynamics (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ben-Naim2008"
literal "false"

\end_inset

), it quantifies states of knowledge on a continuum from complete ignorance
 to perfect certainty.
 Information and uncertainty turn out to be different sides of the same
 coin (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Briggs2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Semantic (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Zhong2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) and syntactic (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chomsky2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) branches of information theory combine into a complementary view.
 These disciplines delve into the realm of human cognition.
 Less mathematically-tractable, they nonetheless provide practical frameworks
 for charactering the state of knowledge on which decisions are based.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Game theory provides the second leg of the Information-Economics tripod.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Birchler1999"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 specifically focus on 
\shape italic
the elementary game
\shape default
.
 Its use serves to explain how market equilibria occur even in the presence
 of information asymmetries (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Brunnermeier2001"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, microeconomic principles bring in the utility perspective.
 Marketplace transactions effect exchanges in utility between counter-parties.
 Desirable transactions are win-win, resulting in net-positive changes to
 counter-parties' collective utility.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Information-Economics concepts are typically applied to explaining the operation
s of transactional markets.
 They explain how, for example, bid and ask prices during negotiation disclose
 counter-parties' proprietary positions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Extending Information Economics principles beyond their transactional context
 comprises our present ambition.
 How do we propose to accomplish this? We shift our focus from information's
 role as a transactional asset to that of a strategic asset along the lines
 suggested by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Drucker1992"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 We want moreover to look beyond the focus in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Drucker1999"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 on operational efficiency.
 Our strategic-impact characterization follows from the utility derived
 from acting on it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Information in a strategic context supports decision-making about marketplace
 positioning, organizational design, and operational alignment 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Leiblein2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The value of strategic information can therefore be quantified in terms
 influencing corporate financials, such as balance-sheet assets and realized
 revenue on income statements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The role advocated here for information's contribution to differentiation
 is not altogether unprecedented.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Teece2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 lists 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Sensing
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 as one of three 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Dynamic Capabilities
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 leading to sustainable enterprise performance (p.
 48).
 Sensing spans systems and processes to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

learn, sense, filter, shape, and calibrate opportunities
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reeves2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 moreover identify 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Signal Advantage
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 as one of five components for 
\shape italic
Adaptive Advantage
\shape default
 (pp.
 87-171).
 Their framework identifies maturity stages beginning with the tactical
 and technical competencies of handling data, to shaping the informational
 landscape.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What then does Information Economics have to contribute to this established
 body of work? We seek — through laying a more-formal undergirding derived
 from economic theory — to provide opportunities for more-systematic characteriz
ation and management of the complexities underlying competitive differentiation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Decision Analysis represents the most-immediate beneficiary to which a theory
 of information-based differentiation might innovatively contribute.
 Thereafter, operational and organizational modeling may also benefit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Information-Economics Concepts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Birchler and Bütler present a view of information that is in a narrow sense
 strategic (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Birchler1999"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 They distinguish between 
\shape italic
strategic
\shape default
 and 
\shape italic
non-strategic
\shape default
 players.
 Given information, strategic players seek to maximize their utility.
 Non-strategic players play blindly.
 In financial economics, some employ this criterion to distinguish between
 investors and gamblers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This leads to our 
\shape italic
essential axiom
\shape default
 from Information Economics: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The value of information is the increase in utility an expects from receiving
 the information 
\shape italic
and
\shape default
 from optimally reacting to it
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "p. 32"
key "Birchler1999"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 We then have two components to our valuation framework.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
The Informational Component of Information Valuation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We first have the information itself.
 We must attribute a degree of confidence to the information.
 We consider it in terms of the extent to which it supports — or not — an
 assertion about a specific state of nature.
 We are only certain of such states on the rarest of occasions.
 Some degree of doubt nearly always burdens us.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 1998 motion picture 
\shape italic
The Red Violin
\shape default
 illustrates through an example resembling one used by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "pp. 5-6"
key "Shafer1976"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The main character — an appraiser of rare musical instruments — is hired
 to inspect a lot to be auctioned off by a world-renowned auction house.
 The lot contains a specimen he suspects might be the lost masterpiece from
 an Italian master craftsman.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our hero begins collecting evidence to establish the instrument's authenticity.
 A lab technician measures acoustic spectra.
 A world-famous virtuoso plays it, then coyly displays ambivalence.
 Minuscule samples of paint and wood are sent for laboratory analysis and
 dating.
 instrument's interior is inspected — using an electro-optical device —
 to discover what appears to be the master craftsman's signature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each piece of evidence in isolation supports to varying degrees our appraiser's
 belief in the instrument's authenticity.
 When the main character assembles them all, he acquires a degree of confidence
 on which to take a substantial risk.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
The Utility-Realization Component of Information Valuation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Acting on our information produces some payoff.
 This arises from our decision to act — or not — given the degree of confidence
 we have in our evidentiary corpus, to borrow a term from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Smets1994"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This is driven by another fundamental principle, the 
\shape italic
von Neumann-Morgenstern axioms
\shape default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "pp. 57-64"
key "Kochebnderfer2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Pettigrew2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 describes 
\shape italic
Epistemic Utility Theory
\shape default
, a closely-related principle (pp.
 1-9).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These guidelines basically tell us to optimize our 
\shape italic
expected
\shape default
 utility.
 What the best outcome is, utility-wise, is based on our organization's
 policies, priorities, appetite for risk, competencies, and other considerations.
 It provides a coherent framework keeping straight the things that matter
 to us.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, in our utility-maximization principle, 
\shape italic
expected
\shape default
 becomes the operative word.
 Our outcomes are very-rarely certain.
 We have two sources of variability that may cause actual outcomes to differ
 from expectations.
 First, we have some residual uncertainty in our information.
 We do not assert with complete certainty that our evidence unequivocally
 supports exactly the state of nature our actions assume.
 This ambiguity weights on what our exceptions are.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Secondly, there may be variability in the affects from actions we take maximize
 our utility.
 We might be outbid in trying to acquire a piece of real estate.
 Or our action might be to launch a capital investment in an IT project.
 Such concerns can be notoriously fraught (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Flyvbjerg2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Seizing — in terms of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Teece2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 — may require us to exercise previously-undemonstrated organizational competenc
ies.
 These may in turn lead to hedging, which further complicates our utility
 calculation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Modes of Information Differentiation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mathematical mechanisms of 
\shape italic
Dempster-Shafer Theory
\shape default
 and 
\shape italic
von Neumann-Morgenstern Axioms
\shape default
 plug very cleanly into each other to give us a formal framework for information
-based differentiation.
 From this we get a rigorous set of tools with which to formally parse our
 present circumstances first described by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Porter1985"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore, how we acquire and evaluate evidence touches on Teece's Sensing
 dynamic capability and Reeve's Sensing advantage.
 The efficacy of our actions in response to our evidence touches on Teece's
 Seizing dynamic capability.
 It also underlies the Organization and Systems advantages from Reeves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Integrating these together scientifically occurs through modeling.
 Tools from Decision Analysis guide us in understanding the strength of
 our evidence.
 They in turn bridge into organizational and operational models to formulate
 beliefs about the efficacy of intended actions.
 Our Information-Economics framework — coupling Dempster-Shafer with von
 Neumann-Morgenstern — provides the mechanisms for integration.
 Treating these principles as axioms leads us to identify three distinct
 modes of information-based differentiation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Getting Evidence that Others Lack.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We refer to this as 
\shape italic
Differentiated Access
\shape default
.
 We enjoy no information advantage from acting on the same body of evidence
 as our competitors.
 We may decide to act differently from them, based on policies, risk appetitive,
 and other considerations.
 But given the same evidentiary base, we should arrive at the same conclusions
 as our competitors about the state of affairs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The disciplines of Business Analytics and insights-extraction-style Artificial
 Intelligence (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Davenport2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) offer one somewhat-technical illustration.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cover1991"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 describe a very fundamental mathematical result telling us that we can
 only do so well with a given data set (pp.
 32-33).
 No amount of clever processing will reduce our residual uncertainty about
 any question beyond limits of the data, given their essential characteristics.
 John Maynard Keynes referred to this as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

irreducible uncertainty
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "p. 739"
key "Keynes1921"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Operating on the same information base as our competitors should not usually
 give us any advantage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Things are different when information asymmetries arise.
 Our 
\shape italic
Red Violin
\shape default
 story offers illustrations.
 Our appraiser was not at first completely forthright with his auction-house
 clients.
 He did not apprise them of all of his evidence-gathering activities, or
 even of his suspicion about the provenance of the violin.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At one point in the story, the superstar virtuoso's reaction was the only
 evidence that the auction-house managers had.
 That information on the surface might tend to refute any suspicions that
 the instrument was anything special.
 Evidence attesting to its authenticity was however piling up on the desk
 of our appraiser.
 He temporarily enjoyed a considerable information advantage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the auction-house managers however started double-checking on the appraiser
's expenses, they recognized the full extent of his evidentiary collection.
 All the cards were then laid out on the table.
 The information advantage vanished.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Seeing Things in the Evidence that Others Overlook.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We refer to this as 
\shape italic
Differentiated Insights
\shape default
.
 Nuance distinguishes this from the previous mode.
 All concerned parties have access to the same body of evidence.
 For the technical reasons described above, any conventional data analytics
 should produce the same results, assuming parity in analytical competencies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One concerned party however reads the evidence differently.
 This might be due to freedom from biases or preconceptions.
 Or, it might arise from an advantage in skills of imagination.
 These lead one to interpret the evidence differently.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our 
\shape italic
Red Violin
\shape default
 illustration, suppose that the auction-house manager knew the superstar
 virtuoso well.
 Perhaps she had dealt with him previously, and knew that he didn't always
 deal forthrightly.
 She might recognize his purported ambivalence about the particular violin
 as disingenuous.
 Her refined musical ear might detect a certain quality to its sound.
 These together might lead her to suspect some unusual and interesting about
 the instrument's provenance.
 Although this evidence was less-strong than that compiled by the appraiser,
 it would not support a conclusion that the violin was 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

nothing special.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Taking Actions Others Cannot.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We call this 
\shape italic
Differentiated Ability to Act
\shape default
.
 When no information asymmetries exist, the greatest expected utility accrues
 to those with the strongest efficacy of means.
 In the case of our 
\shape italic
Red Violin
\shape default
 illustration, once the instrument reached open auction recognized as an
 authentic lost masterpiece, it was beyond the reach of our appraiser.
 Only the well-financed could hope to offer winning bids.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In terms of the Dynamic Capabilities from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Teece2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Differentiated Ability to Act is about Seizing.
 Once multiple parties have sensed an opportunity, the greatest utility
 should accrue to whomever can decisively engage sufficient resources.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reeves2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 touches on this primarily through Organization and Systems advantages.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Advantage from Differentiated Access
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We live in an era of data ubiquity.
 That differentiated access might confer an advantage perhaps seems counterintui
tive.
 To reiterate, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Porter1996"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 cautions that, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

A company can outperform rivals only if it can establish a difference that
 it can preserve.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Publicly available information, e.g.
 on the Internet, usually does not obviously confer this.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Data-access differentiation is actually rather difficult to achieve.
 The Efficient Market Hypothesis from financial economics 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Sec. 7.C.c"
key "Birchler1999"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 asserts that information advantages don't generally exist.
 Having data — or their derivative, information — that competitors lack
 depends on operating models that produce them.
 Apart from such a model, differentiated data-access — whether for individuals
 or organizations — is quite uncommon (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chamoroo2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In fact, differentiated information accrues to organizations deliberately
 designed to produce it.
 To extrapolate from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Drucker1992"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, when information becomes the decisive asset, staking out differentiated
 positions in the marketplace must consider its role.
 Information must be included within the portfolio of assets by which strategy
 is realized.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To the extent that differentiating information-focused competencies depend
 on technology, the latter must also be addressed as a facet of strategy
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kane2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ross2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 explicitly describe frameworks for translating operating models into technology
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

foundations for execution
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Exemplary Positions Based on Differentiated Access
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now consider two operating models providing differentiated information
 access.
 Both examples happen to be technology-based.
 This does not imply however that all such instances are so.
 Many of the most-obvious contemporary examples do however fit this pattern.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Platform business models emerged as a powerful force during the first two
 decades of the 21
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
st
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Century (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Iansiti2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 They have arguably changed the rules of strategy for some sectors of the
 economy.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VanAlstyne2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 asserts that network effects of platforms assume an importance analogous
 to those from scale economies in traditional pipeline business models.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Platforms excel in one particular context.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Evans2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 specifically observes that they have captured the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

broker
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 role of connecting counter-parties in transactions.
 They supplant predecessor media such as newspaper want ads and telephone-book
 yellow pages, to illustrate by retail commerce.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How do platforms produce proprietary information? They act as mediators
 in transactions.
 Counter-parties — individually and collectively — volunteer information
 in exchange for mediation services.
 Much of this remains closely-held.
 The volume of information increases with participant population.
 The volume of counter-party-connection information in fact increases exponentia
lly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Amazon exemplifies this affect most-conspicuously.
 The breadth of its perspective of the retail industry is difficult to comprehen
d.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bond2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 describes how the company has begun exploiting its position to assimilate
 some of the more-valuable value-chain links previously served by suppliers.
 Deep insights into both sides of retail transactions confer an advantageous
 position.
 Wen and Zhu 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Wen2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 describe how platform operators' incursions into complementors' market
 scopes lead to pronounced strategic conundrums for the latter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The playbook for successful platform launches contains rules not counterintuitiv
e to business strategists familiar with other operating models.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bonchek2013a"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Edelman2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Zhu2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 describe some of them.
 The platform market model begins with identifying a defensible position.
 Proprietary information about participants may not be immediately available.
 A plan to draw in initial users using only publicly-available information
 is often required.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bungay2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 explicitly addresses a strategic approach commonly followed by platform
 operators.
 They price competitively — even providing their offerings below-cost, even
 free — in order to capture market share.
 Market share becomes the overriding imperative given network affects, and
 the informational advantage they provide.
 Bungay's pipeline analogy — asserting that efficiency accrues through learning-
curve-like affects — might actually be pessimistic in the case of platforms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Connected-Systems Operating Models.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
