\end_layout

\end_inset

 (IoT) operating models produce information through extensive instrumentation
 of operations.
 Their affects accrue largely to traditional pipeline business models.
 Well-conceived instrumentation of products delivered to customers and internal
 systems by which they are produced can yield windfalls of otherwise-unavailable
 information.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Porter and Heppelmann 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Porter2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 describe the external-marketplace facet of IoT.
 Instrumenting products represents the most-common example.
 This insinuates platform-like advantages into pipeline operating models.
 Patterns of customers' product usages are measured and recorded by the
 manufacturer.
 These mechanisms enable new modes Teece's Sensing dynamic capability and
 the Signal Advantage of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reeves2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly, Porter and Heppelmann 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Porter2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 also describe the internal-operations side of connected systems.
 Instrumentation of internal systems, processes, and procedures represents
 the focus.
 Organizations' dark corners are illuminated.
 Opportunities thereby arise to improve operational effectiveness and adaptabili
ty.
 These solutions support the Organization and Systems Advantages described
 by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reeves2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
