\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to business.
 They assert a causal chain from interconnecting to information sharing
 to shared situational awareness to mission effectiveness.
 These represent the principal internal benefits of connected systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Defensibility of Positions Based on Differentiated Access
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We previously offered a platform business model as an example of a scenario
 for data-access differentiation.
 Platforms — intermediaries that connect two or more distinct parties and
 
\shape italic
orchestrate
\shape default
 their transactions (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Zhu2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) inherently generate information about their users.
 Broadly-adopted platforms tend to enjoy formidable barriers to replication
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Iansiti2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More generally, market leaders in highly-concentrated industries tend to
 enjoy operationally-generated information advantages.
 Walmart provides an obvious example (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hyde2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 The bargaining power derived by concentration and scale in the distribution
 chain has drawn attention for decades (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Fein1999"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 This advantage is compounded by information asymmetries.
 Information-sharing between key industry players potentially heightens
 replication barriers (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dance2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So, under what circumstances might these data-access-based advantages become
 vulnerable? Stickiness becomes key defensive tactic for the platform operator.
 Forrester consultants 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Manning2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 argue in a more-general context that, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Customer experience is the single greatest predictor of whether customers
 will return—or defect to a competitor.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A sustainable platform then makes switching undesirable or inconvenient.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Market-share leaders in highly-concentrated industry segments tend only
 to be unseated by market restructuring.
 Bryce and Dyer 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bryce2007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 describe outsider strategies have been applied to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

crack well-guarded markets
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 These are often about insurgency through clever market positioning, or
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

disruptive innovation
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Christensen2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 The latter sometimes arises from discerning and exploiting opportunities
 to which incumbents are blind.
 But industry-structure shifts do not occur frequently.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Connected-systems business models principally benefit industry incumbents.
 Would-be new entrants can potentially offer ancillary services to help
 pipeline-model incumbents realize connected-systems solutions.
 Replicating existing assets of a pipeline-business however represents a
 formidable barrier.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Difficulties in replication of technology competencies needed for both platform
 and connected-systems operating models may lead value-chain restructuring
 in some industries.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "McLain2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 describes a potentially-foreshadowing automotive-manufacturing illustration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Specifically, the costs of key technologies underpinning emerging value
 propositions in that industry exceed what some manufacturers can organically
 develop.
 Examples include artificial intelligence needed for self-driving vehicles
 and electric drive trains for zero- and low-emission automobiles (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "McLain2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 If these competencies become too hard to replicate, the attractiveness
 of value-chain segments controlled by incumbents may diminish.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Advantage from Differentiated Insights
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Differentiated Insights involve imaginative exercise of sensing competencies
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Teece2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reeves2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) to see things that are hidden in plain-sight.
 Viewing the landscape from unorthodox perspectives often produces them.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lewis2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 suggests, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Heresy is good: Heresy means opportunity.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We observed above that generally-available data provide few opportunities
 for information asymmetries.
 This is after all the basis of the Efficient-Market Hypothesis.
 Occasionally however, windows of opportunity do in fact open.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Differentiated insights may or may not come from technology.
 In the case of insights-extraction-style Artificial Intelligence (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Davenport2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

), we previously noted limitations due to Keynes' 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

irreducible-uncertainty
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Keynes1921"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 This potentially bounds the benefits our sensing competency when applying
 analytics to publicly-available data.
 Is this ever beatable?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It turns out that we can 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

beat
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Keynes limit, in a way.
 We do this by considering our evidence from unusual, insightful perspectives.
 This might mean not taking them at face value.
 This perspective might involve adding to data contextual information they
 do not explicitly contain themselves.
 It might also result from imagination or vision placing one organization
 ahead of the rest of the industry.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Described by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Christensen2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Disruptive Innovation exemplifies a non-technology form of differentiated
 insights.
 Would-be disruptors detect chinks in the armor of established incumbents.
 They consequently become capable of siphoning off the some latter's market
 share in specific segments.
 Christensen, 
\emph on
et al
\emph default
, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Christensen2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 assert a narrow definition of disruption.
 We can however extend our consideration the more-general span of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

substitutes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 from the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Five Forces
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 framework by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "pp. 34-37"
key "Porter1990"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Exemplary Positions Based on Differentiated Insights
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider here two illustrations of differentiated-insights advantage.
 Our first example is technology-focused.
 Specifically it shows differentiation using business-analytics and decision
 analysis.
 These lie in the vein of insights-extraction-style Artificial Intelligence
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Davenport2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 This principally illustrates Teece's Sensing dynamic capability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We alternatively consider an operating-model case based on disruptive innovation
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Christensen2004,Christensen2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 This operational illustration also incorporates Teece's Seizing dynamic
 capability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Technology-Derived Differentiated Insights.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Michael Lewis' novel 
\shape italic
Moneyball
\shape default
 tells the story of the U.S.
 Major League Baseball team Oakland, CA Athletics (As) (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lewis2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 The Oakland As successfully competed against teams with much larger player-sala
ry budgets.
 They accomplished this through a player-contribution valuation model that
 was considerably more-insightful than competitors'.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To illustrate, the 2002 As paid an average salary of slightly less then
 $1.5 million.
 This was substantively less than the industry average of $2.3 million.
 Their novel player-valuation criteria afforded flexibility to consider
 opportunities that competitors overlooked.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A novel set of utility criteria was part of the As' approach.
 Winning games was their principal objective.
 This was part of a tradeoff underlying decisions to allow superstar players
 like Jason Giambi go to other teams.
 Such stars produce higher revenues through ticket sales and merchandising.
 Their individual contributions to total games won could however be distributed
 across multiple other judiciously-selected players.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The As' utility metric is illuminating.
 For the 2002 season they won the second-most games in all of major-league
 baseball.
 Their cost per win in terms of player salaries were about $525,000.
 This was one and three-quarters of a standard deviation below the major-league
 average of around $1 million per regular-season win.
 Moreover, their revenue-to-salary ratio was about 1.2 standard deviations
 above the major-league average of 1.54.
 They were third-best of all major-league clubs by the latter metric.
 This differentiated-insights strategy apparently worked well both in terms
 of on-field and business measures of performance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These statistics allow us to cursorily illustrate attribution of value to
 player-contribution information for the Oakland As.
 They finished the regular season four games ahead of division runner-up
 Anaheim Angels, which paid $747,000 in player salary per win.
 The Angeles incidentally were the third-most efficient major-league team
 in terms of salary-per-win.
 They ranked behind the As and the Minnesota Twins, who eliminated the former
 in the divisional round of the playoffs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The information to identify players needed to achieve the As four-win advantage
 over the Angels could therefore be valued at $2.1 million.
 Given these efficiencies, the Angels might have prevailed at a cost of
 slightly less than $3 million in additional salary expenditures.
 These summaries assume the organizations' costs to acquire players are
 approximately equal and obviously ignore confidence intervals and other
 statistical measures of variation.
 But we do get a sense of the utility-focused reasoning employed in information
 economics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Beyond or professional-sports illustration, anecdotal evidence shows similar
 patterns in the financial sector.
 Wiggelsworth and Fortado 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Wigglesworth2018a"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 describe a more-recent attempt to apply a differentiated-insight approach
 to investing.
 Parity may also be occurring in algorithmic trading (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Wigglesworth2018b"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Differentiated Insights Leading to Disruptive Operating Models.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Christensen, 
\emph on
et al
\emph default
, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Christensen2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 offer so-called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

discount
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 airline carriers as an example of disruptive innovation (pp.129 - 153).
 Exemplified most-frequently by Southwest Airlines, these businesses conform
 to a narrow definition 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Christensen2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

  of disruptive innovation.
 By this characterization, a disruptor offers to a judiciously-selected
 market segment a simplified substitute for an incumbent attempting to serve
 multiple segments.
 The former typically differentiates based on cost.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Southwest Airlines in particular designed a very lean operation.
 They pursued operational efficiency through elimination of variability
 in operating-cost drivers.
 They also focused on single-segment routes so that they could maximize
 aircraft utilization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This case principally illustrates application of the sensing competencies
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Teece2009,Reeves2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Southwest judiciously selected routes to use as entry points.
 Attractive candidates were likely to yield high aircraft utilization combined
 with gates at airports that were initially underutilized.
 For example, they selected Baltimore-Washington International Airport (BWI)
 as their entry point into the Washington, DC market.
 After establishing itself at BWI, Southwest moved into other airports in
 the heart of the DC metro area.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Defensibility of Positions Based on Differentiated Insights
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But just how defensible is this sort of differentiation? Results vary depending
 upon whether or not competitive advantage accrues from a technology-based
 solution.
 Such solutions tend to offer relatively low barriers to imitation.
 Monopolization of the best quantitative talent by any one organization
 is unlikely (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Willhite2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 A popular quip states, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The smartest people in the world don't all work for us.
 Most of them work for somebody else.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\shape italic
Moneyball
\shape default
 bears this out.
 The Oakland As for awhile used statistical-analysis services by an outside
 firm, AVM systems.
 They subsequently migrated this capability in-house.
 Mathematical knowledge on which analytics are based is fungible.
 So are individuals with deep expertise in its use (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Willhite2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Moreover, outsourcing of strategically key functions is ill-advised (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Sameer2004,Hamlett2007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 The As were competing on analytics.
 They needed this capability in-house.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And what about the As' sophisticated player-valuation model? Recent studies
 by sports economists reveal these valuation methods have gone mainstream.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Brown2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Congdon-Hohman2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 report evidence of their widespread adoption.
 Some of the so-called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

power statistics
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 — central to the As' player valuations — are even reported on scoreboards
 at major-league ballparks! This arbitrage opportunity is history.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Southwest Airlines' position as a disruptive innovator proves more-durable.
 The carrier continues to deliver above-industry results both in terms of
 passenger satisfaction and financial performance.
 It has also expanded into some hub airports charging higher gate fees.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This durability arises from its operating model.
 Southwest's operational and organizational designs prove difficult for
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

traditional
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 carriers to replicate.
 The latter are designed to simultaneously serve multiple market segments.
 Pressure from low-cost carriers has forced them to make services more-austere
 for passengers purchasing tickets in lower fare classes.
 This however occurs at the cost of diminished passenger satisfaction in
 the corresponding market segments.
 Southwest Airlines however maintains predictable — although not luxurious
 — levels of service.
 It thereby avoids customer-dissatisfaction issues.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Advantage from Differentiated Ability to Act
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Merely acquiring information is insufficient.
 The differentiating modes described above emphasized sensing competencies
 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Teece2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reeves2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Action upon the resulting knowledge must occur to realize value from it.
 This is the essence of Teece's Seizing Dynamic Capability.
 In information-economics terms, we speak here of utility realized through
 acting in knowledge.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The ability to act represents a central consideration underlying organizational
 design (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Denison1995,Groysberg2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Suarez2005"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 studied different industry-volatility scenarios.
 Industry change rates can be characterized in terms of market-evolution
 and technology-evolution dimensions.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Moore2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 associated rates of change with distinct stages in market lifecycles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Different types of information and assume greater degrees of importance
 depending on industry dynamics.
 When industries are in 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Calm Waters
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 — in terms of the framework by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Suarez2005"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 — information about operational consistency and conformity are of highest
 importance.
 The degrees organization and systems adaptivities from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reeves2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 might be intentionally low.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To the extent that organizational agility and dynamism depend on technology,
 the systems themselves must mirror those attributes.
 Ross, 
\emph on
et al
\emph default
, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ross2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 warn against circumstances in which the technology assets 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fossilize
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 their organizations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Exemplary Positions Based on Differentiated Ability to Act
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lynch2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 presents a case study illustrating an auto manufacturer's ability to act
 in response to a supply-chain disruption.
 This illustrated judicious use of information without explicit reference
 to technology systems by which it is managed and exploited.
 Adaptivity does not necessarily depend on technology.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On March 11, 2011, a Richter 9.1 earthquake struck off the Northwest coast
 of Honshu, Japan.
 The Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster was the most-visible consequence.
 Other less-dire impacts to global business also occurred, however.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A fire broke out at a paint-pigment manufacturing facility operated by Merck
 KGaA in Onahama.
 The Merck plant was the world's sole source for Xirallic, used to make
 car coatings sparkle.
 This introduced a bottleneck impacting a large swath of the auto-manufacturing
 industry.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Of the major manufacturers, Hyundai alone sought and introduced substitutes
 into its operations (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Seetharaman2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Its competitors sustained production backlogs.
 Hyundai incurred costs to reconfigure its assembly lines.
 This adaptivity however allowed it to capture market share at the expense
 of less-adaptive competitors.
\end_layout

