 A differentiated ability to act therefore appears to be the most-defensible
 mode of information-based competitive advantage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Conclusions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In an information-driven economy, information becomes a decisive asset.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Drucker1992"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 foresaw that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

knowledge 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle$
\end_inset

becomes
\begin_inset Formula $\rangle$
\end_inset

 a more-crucial economic resource than land, labor, or financial assets....
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Subsequent business-strategy frameworks — most-notably 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Teece2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Reeves2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 — consider this through competency views of competitive advantage.
 Each refers to a 
\shape italic
Sensing
\shape default
 capability.
 These address how organizations acquire and interpret information to formulate
 pictures of their competitive landscapes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We describe here an information-economics formalism undergirding to these
 competency frameworks for differentiation.
 We combine principles from 
\shape italic
Theory of Evidence
\shape default
 with 
\shape italic
Utility Maximization
\shape default
.
 They together provide a formal structure for thinking about information-based
 differentiation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Treating these concepts as axioms leads to three distinct modes of deriving
 advantage from informational asymmetries.
 We can acquire information that others do not have.
 This results primarily through business models deliberately designed to
 produce it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can alternatively achieve information asymmetries through differentiated
 insights.
 This amounts to seeing things — hidden in plain sight — within the evidence
 that others may have missed.
 This might occur due to freedom from biases encumbering others, or from
 a sharper sense of imagination.
 Recognizing opportunities for disruption fits in this category.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, we might exercise a greater ability to take action given a recognized
 state affairs supported by the commonly available evidence.
 These advantages accrue due to aspects of organizational factors.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Teece2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 particularly emphasizes these in his 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Seizing
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

"
\end_layout

\end_inset

 dynamic capability.
 In the absence of information asymmetries, the most-capable organization
 should realize the greatest utility from an opportunity.
 This mode of information-based differentiation turns out to be the hardest
 to replicate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The formalism of this information-economics approach to differentiation
 offers the potential to address questions of competitiveness more-systematicall
y than perhaps otherwise.
 It provides a mathematical structure to unify different management-science
 disciplines.
 The most-immediate benefits accrue to Decision Analysis.
 Subsequently, closer integration with organizational and operational modeling
 appear practical.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
onecolumn
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

